So, most dashboards I'd envision will have multiple tabs with multiple matplotlib/plots per tab. To clean this up a little, I've been writing functions in a separate file (maybe config.py or plots.py) that output either a matplotlib figure or the HTML associated with a bokeh plot.

Then in the app class definition I write the following:
    
    if params['output_id'] == 'output_1':
        return config.plot_func_1(params)
    if params['output_id'] == 'output_2':
        return config.plot_func_2(params)
    .
    .
    .
    if params['output_id'] == 'output_n':
        return config.plot_func_n(params)

A simple improvement would be to create a server.App class method that takes the output id, the return function and the params and either returns the result of the function or passes. Something like this:

    def output(output_id, func, params, *args, **kwargs):
        if params['output_id'] == output_id:
            return func(params, *args, **kwargs)
        else:
            pass

Which in the above example would look like this:

    self.output('output_1', get_plot_1, params)
    self.output('output_2', get_plot_2, params)
    .
    .
    .
    self.output('output_n', get_plot_n, params)

I think the main benefit would be that you aren't crowding up the app definition with lots of conditionals and return statements.

My python skills are not fantastic, but I am also beginning to imagine the use of decorators to define output functions.

So in my config.py file where I am defining all my plots I would be able to do the following:

    @output('output_1', 'getPlot')
    def get_plot_1(params)
        #My Plot Code
        return figure

    @output('output_2', 'getHTML')
    def get_plot_2(params):
        #My HTML Code
        return html

And then the respective getXXXX methods would be populated accordingly.

I'm not really sure how we would implement the above, but I guess one question is whether this would be useful. The second question would be whether this is a good interface.

Your thoughts? I'd be happy to work on implementing the first part if there is interest. As far as the second part we'd have to flesh out the details and then look into implementation.

As reported in [_pslinux.py](https://github.com/giampaolo/psutil/blob/master/psutil/_pslinux.py#L840) we have 3 formats for diskstats reporting information:

1. 15 fields if we use a Linux 2.4 kernel;
2. 14 fields if we use a Linux 2.6+ kernel and it reports a partition;
3. 7 fields if we use a Linux 2.6+ kernel and it reports a disk.

In fact, if we use a 2.6+ kernel, we have always a 14 fields structure (I've verified on CentOS 6 and CentOS 7), so the method reports always the same data. Is a good thing to correct this documentation and remove the unused code for cleanup (it also a good thing to check if the data are correct in case of disk or partition check)

